Existing medical devices primarily rely on reactive runtime diagnostics and post-failure troubleshooting for identifying embedded software instability and performance degradation. Current systems generally monitor static resource thresholds such as CPU and memory usage but do not effectively detect progressive runtime degradation trends including memory growth, latency drift, thread starvation, communication bottlenecks, or correlated subsystem instability.

As medical devices become increasingly software-driven and operate continuously for extended durations, intelligent runtime optimization and predictive stability analysis become important for improving reliability and reducing downtime.

The proposed invention introduces an AI-assisted runtime optimization framework capable of identifying abnormal runtime behavior and degradation trends before visible subsystem instability or software failure occurs.











The invention provides several advantages over existing runtime monitoring systems by enabling predictive runtime degradation detection instead of reactive troubleshooting after subsystem instability occurs. The framework continuously analyzes correlated operational metrics including CPU usage, memory utilization, thread behavior, process latency, and communication performance to identify abnormal runtime trends before visible failure occurs.

Additional advantages include improved embedded software stability, early memory leak detection, reduced unexpected downtime, faster troubleshooting, improved resource utilization efficiency, runtime health scoring, and intelligent optimization recommendations. The invention also improves long-duration operational reliability for embedded medical devices while maintaining separation from therapy delivery and patient-critical functionality.




The invention is currently at conceptual and prototype evaluation stage. Initial proof-of-concept architecture has been defined for monitoring embedded runtime operational metrics including CPU utilization, memory usage, process latency, runtime health scores, thread activity, and communication performance.

The current prototype scope includes AI-assisted anomaly detection for identifying progressive runtime degradation trends and abnormal resource utilization patterns. Initial feasibility analysis indicates that long-duration runtime instability and performance degradation trends can be identified using correlated operational metrics before visible subsystem slowdown or software failure occurs.

The framework is intended as a non-clinical advisory runtime optimization system and does not modify therapy delivery or patient-critical functionality.






The invention originated as part of an internal innovation initiative focused on improving embedded medical device runtime reliability, operational stability, and software resource optimization. The concept is applicable to modular medical device platforms utilizing embedded Linux environments, SOM-based architectures, long-duration runtime services, UI rendering frameworks, and software-driven subsystem interfaces.

The invention is currently being explored as a future embedded runtime optimization and predictive stability enhancement framework. At present, the invention is not part of any finalized commercial product release and remains within internal conceptual evaluation and prototype planning activities.





The inventors are aware that runtime monitoring and resource optimization technologies exist in embedded computing, enterprise infrastructure, and cloud environments. However, no specific internal invention disclosures or patents are currently known that combine AI-assisted runtime anomaly detection, predictive performance degradation analysis, runtime health scoring, and embedded medical device optimization within a unified operational framework.

The proposed invention differs by focusing on intelligent embedded runtime stability analysis for modular medical devices operating continuously for extended durations. Contributors have not conducted a formal patent or competitive search at this stage.






